functionEntry.documentation:
Convert a URL string into a percent-encoded string.
The reserved characters in the string will be replaced with their corresponding
hex-value pairs. This follows the URI-encoding scheme as detailed by RFC 3986

[String] url The URL string to be encoded

@since 1.1.2

functionEntry.name: makeJsonRequest
functionEntry.documentation:
To use Garmin Connect Mobile as a proxy to the web, use makeJsonRequest().
The request is asynchronous; the responseCallback will be called when the request returns.
[String] url The URL being requested

[Dictionary] parameters Dictionary of keys and values, appended to the URL as a GET request or set as the body for a POST request. Can be null.

[Dictionary] options Dictionary of options. Can be null.

@option options [Number] :method The HTTP method of the request. Should be a HTTP_REQUEST_METHOD_* value.
@option options [Dictionary] :headers A Dictionary of HTTP headers to include in the request. The "Content-Type"
header can be specified using a REQUEST_CONTENT_TYPE_* value. If the content
type is not specified, it will default to "appllication/json" for GET and
DELETE requests, and will default to "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" for
POST and PUT requests.
[Method] responseCallback This is a callback in the format function responseCallback(responseCode, data);

responseCode has the server response code, and data contains a Dictionary of content if the request was successful.
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: makeImageRequest
functionEntry.documentation:
To request an image through Garmin Connect Mobile, call makeImageRequest(). GCM
will scale and dither the image based on the capabilities of the device, but
the user will be able to pass additional options (like dithering it down to a
one color image)
[String] url URL of image to request

[Dictionary] parameters Dictionary of keys and values, appended to the URL. Can be null.

[Dictionary] options Additional image options

@option options [Array] :palette The color palette to restrict the image dithering to. Using a smaller palette can reduce the size of the image data to speed up transfers.
@option options [Number] :maxWidth The maximum width an image should be scaled to
@option options [Number] :maxHeight The maximum height an image should be scaled to
@option options [Number] :dithering The type of dithering to use when processing the image. Defaults to Floyd-Steinberg.
[Method] responseCallback This is a callback in the format function responseCallback(responseCode, data);

responseCode has the server response code, and data contains a WatchUi.BitmapResource if it was successful.
@since 1.2.0

Use createSession() to create a session object with options determined by the caller.
Only one session object is allowed to exist at a time. If there

discard() methods, this method will return that object instead of creating a new one.

@option options :sport The primary sport being recorded (SPORT_GENERIC by default)
@option options :subSport The sport subcategory being recorded (SUB_SPORT_GENERIC by default)
@option options [String] :name Required. This is the name that will be associated with the sport being recorded. The suggested maximum length of the name is 15 characters (some devices support longer names).
Returns [Session] A new session object, or the existing session object if a session is active and has not been saved or discarded

functionEntry.name: onLayout
functionEntry.documentation:
The entry point for the View is onLayout(). This is called before the
View is shown to load resources and set up the layout of the View.
[Graphics.Dc] dc The drawing context

Returns [Boolean] true if handled, false otherwise

@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: onShow
functionEntry.documentation:
When the View is brought into the foreground, onShow() is called. This is
where you should load resources into system memory for use in this view.
Returns [Boolean] true if handled, false otherwise

@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: onUpdate
functionEntry.documentation:
When a View is active, onUpdate() is used to update
dynamic content. This function is called when
the View is brought to the foreground. For widgets and
watch-apps it is also called when WatchUi.requestUpdate()
is called. For watchfaces it is called once a minute and
for datafields it is called once a second. If a class that
extends View does not implement this function then any
Drawables contained in the View will automatically be drawn.
[Graphics.Dc] dc The drawing context

Returns [Boolean] true if handled, false otherwise

@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: onHide
functionEntry.documentation:
Before the View is removed from the foreground, onHide() is called. Here
you should free resources from memory if you are planning on leaving this
view on the page stack.
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: setLayout
functionEntry.documentation:
Use setLayout() to set the layout for the View. If the extending class
does not override onUpdate(), then all Drawables contained in layout will
automatically be drawn by the View.
[Layout] layout An array of Drawables

functionEntry.name: onTimerStart
functionEntry.documentation:
The function onTimerStart will be called when the activity timer goes from the
stopped state to the started state. If the activity timer is running when the
app is loaded, this event will run immediately after startup.
@since 2.0.0

functionEntry.name: onTimerStop
functionEntry.documentation:
The function onTimerStop will be called when the activity timer goes from the
running state to the stopped state.
@since 2.0.0

functionEntry.name: onTimerPause
functionEntry.documentation:
The function onTimerPause will be called when the activity timer goes from the
running state to the paused state. The paused state will occur when the
auto-pause feature pauses the timer. If the activity timer is paused when the
app is loaded, this event will run immediately after startup
@since 2.0.0

functionEntry.name: onTimerResume
functionEntry.documentation:
The function onTimerResume will be called when the activity timer goes from the
paused state to the running state.
@since 2.0.0

functionEntry.name: onTimerLap
functionEntry.documentation:
The function onTimerLap will be called when a lap is added to the current activity
@since 2.0.0

functionEntry.name: onTimerReset
functionEntry.documentation:
The function onTimerReset will be called when the current activity is ended
@since 2.0.0
